1. Product Overview

Trek turns a vague idea ("coffee → food → museum → sunset → Griffith") into a costed, timed, optimized day. Before leaving the house, a user sees the full route, total drive time, gas cost, per-stop and total budget, weather windows, and a schedule. Activity cards are draggable; reordering instantly recomputes route, ETA, budget, and gas.

After the day happens, a user can flip the same venture into a public post — itinerary in order, map preview, photos per stop, per-place ratings/reviews, an overall day rating, caption, and tags. Other users discover these in a social feed, read place-level reviews, and copy the route into their own planner with one tap.

Two product loops:


Planning loop (utility): create venture → add cards → optimize → see cost/time/weather → save.
Social loop (growth): complete a day → publish with reviews/photos → others discover → copy route → new venture. The copy action is the viral engine.


A lightweight Ideation Folder system lets users dump TikTok/Instagram links into folders now (URL only — no scraping/transcription yet) and convert them into itinerary ideas later.


2. User Personas

1. "Planner Paige" — 24, lives in Irvine.
Plans date nights and friend hangs. Wants to know exactly what a day costs before committing. Hates surprise gas + parking + food math. Core value: budget control + no decision fatigue.

2. "Explorer Eli" — 29, content-adjacent.
Saves dozens of TikToks of cool LA spots and never does anything with them. Wants a graveyard-of-links to become real plans. Core value: Ideation Folders → itineraries.

3. "Social Sofia" — 21, micro-creator.
Documents her food crawls and museum days. Wants a cleaner, more useful Beli — where her review is attached to a route, not just a single restaurant. Core value: publishing routes + place reviews, getting saves/likes.

4. "Copycat Chris" — 26, new to a city / decision-averse.
Doesn't want to plan; wants to run someone else's proven day. Core value: discover feed + one-tap copy route. (This persona drives retention and is the cheapest to acquire.)


